explanation:
To determine whether OS_TimeBaseDelete violates the MISRA C for-loop well-formedness rule we must inspect any for-loops and side-effecting behaviour in the function and in any functions whose behaviour is considered part of the for-loop body. Although OS_TimeBaseDelete itself has no for statement, the MISRA rule treats called functions' behaviour as part of a loop body, so the bodies of its callees (and their callees) must be examined. Explanations per symbol: 

- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl: called at start to check context; its body must be checked for any for-loops or side effects that could conflict with the rule when considered part of this function's behaviour. 
- OS_TaskGetId_Impl: argument to OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl; its behavior may include loops or side effects and thus must be inspected. 
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: main lookup routine called by OS_TimeBaseDelete; its implementation can contain loops (and side effects) that must be analyzed. 
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include because any loops/side effects in it contribute to the behaviour of calls originating from OS_TimeBaseDelete. 
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById (and used by other object-id routines); inspect for loops/side effects. 
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; its body could modify objects used as loop counters or have persistent side effects. 
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include for the same reason. 
- OS_TimeBaseDelete_Impl: performs the target-specific deletion; its implementation may contain for-loops or modify objects relevant to loop well-formedness and must be inspected. 
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: called by OS_TimeBaseDelete_Impl; include to analyze any loops or side effects in the deletion path. 
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: called to complete the delete; its implementation may include loops or persistent side effects (including notification) that must be checked. 
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: callee of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete; include because loops/side effects here are part of the delete completion behavior. 
- OS_NotifyEvent: callee of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete; notifications often iterate over listeners — potential for-loops that must be examined. 

Additionally the following types and macros/constants used in OS_TimeBaseDelete are required to understand semantics and control-flow decisions that influence whether any loops in callees are reachable or what objects may be modified: 

- OS_object_token_t: token type passed between object-id routines and delete implementation; required to follow what is modified by callees. 
- osal_id_t: type of timer_id parameter; needed to trace how it is used/modified across calls. 
- osal_objtype_t: object-type return from OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl used in the early state-check. 
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE: constant compared to objtype; required to know which code paths are taken. 
- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE: mode passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById that may affect internal behavior/loops. 
- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE: returned when context is invalid; needed to determine whether subsequent calls (and their loops) can be reached. 
- OS_SUCCESS: used to check result of OS_ObjectIdGetById and decide whether to call delete routines.

These symbols let the next analyst examine all reachable function bodies and the relevant types/constants to decide if any for statements (in the target or in any called function considered part of its behaviour) violate MISRA's for-loop well-formedness constraints.
